div.div:
$TEK is the base DAO token that acts the the equity share to allocate capital.
$TEK is a rebasing token. This means it has no set supply. The supply changes based on the data used in the calculation.
Supply changes are proportional across all holders. This is similar to Ampleforth and Aave "C" tokens.

div.div:
$XTEK is also a rebasing token.
When capital is allocated such that is is encumbered by debt, the $XTEK token will automatically change it's supply because the data points being indexed will show a balance change.
The encumbering of capital with debt means that capital is no longer being indexed to contribute to the supply of $TEK.
This means that when capital becomes available that is not encumbered by debt the contribution to the supply of $TEK will be proportionally distributed to all holders. Even if the supply was 0. This means that the vault will control the same percentage of available capital as was held to secure the minimum LTV requirements.

div.div:
A user stakes their $TEK to borrow $WBTC. Because this encumbers that capital with debt, it ceases to contribute to the supply of $TEK. By accepting this $TEK for deposit, the supply contraction can be scoped to just the staked tokens.
The total amount staked will be converted to $XTEK through the rebase. This is because the capital is being used as collateral. So even though only a portion is at risk of liquidation at any time, the total amount is at risk for the life of the loan.

div.div:
Vault moves $DAI from a purely lending position to a separate deposit flagged to use as collateral. Because collateral is still available for lending, it continues to earn interest. But must be compartmentalized from capital other users have not chosen to put at risk for liquidation.
The vault also swaps a portion of it's $cDAI to purely lending $WBTC, receiving $cWBTC. The amount matches the amount of debt token produced. Thus this amount is higher then the amount borrowed due to the inclusion of the liquidation fee. Because the vault is holding the majority of $TEK, there should always be liquidity to match user's positions.
